ML2 - Regression¶

A project by Khon Hoang Nguyen and Dustin Pacholleck

This part of the project was done in the Kaggle environment and points to the kaggle dataset directly.

Introduction¶

Evaluating coffee beans¶

The goal of this machine learning project is to predict the total cup poins a bean gets.
Three certified graders evaluate the coffee based on a 100-point system, and the scores of the three cuppers are averaged to produce a this score.

Since this projects aims to predict this score based on variables available at the time of purchase. We will focus on the following variables.

Rare Feature Encoding¶

Some features appear very seldom and do not hold enough information for generalization. Therefore, those rare features will be recoded as 'Other'. Again, to avoid any data leakage only features seen in training set will be respected. Unknown features in the test set will be also encoded as 'Other'.

In [16]:
# Rare feature encoding
for col in list(X.select_dtypes(include='object')):
    freqs = X_train[col].value_counts(normalize=True)
    
    frequent_cat = [
        x for x in freqs.loc[freqs > 0.05].index.values]

    X_train[col] = np.where(
        X_train[col].isin(frequent_cat),
        X_train[col], "Other")
    
    X_test[col] = np.where(
        X_test[col].isin(frequent_cat),
        X_test[col], "Other")

Feature Transformation¶

The feature transformation can be done in various ways and various algorithms are more or less prone to different ways of transformation.
All algorithms require some sort of categorial encoding which is done with the OneHotEncoder. Previously, we already made sure that rare categories are grouped as 'Other' to deflate the number of categories.
For numerical encoding some algorithms require prior scaling and others do not. Here we decide based on the algorihm.

For this a pipeline is set up to avoid any chance of data leakage.

In [115]:
## defining a pipeline, takes care of scalar creation, encoding, and model fit
def model_pipeline(model, numTransform = True):
    # Numeric
    if numTransform == True:
        numeric_features = list(set(X_train.columns).intersection(set(num_var)))
        numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
          ('scaler', StandardScaler())
        ])
    
        # Categorical
        categorical_features = list(set(X_train.columns).intersection(set(cat_var)))
        categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
              ('encoder', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown = 'ignore'
                                        ))
        ])

        # Preprocessor
        preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
            transformers=[
            ('numeric', numeric_transformer, numeric_features),
            ('categorical', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
            ]) 
    else:     
        # Categorical
        categorical_features = list(set(X_train.columns).intersection(set(cat_var)))
        categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
              ('encoder', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown = 'ignore'
                                        ))
        ])

        # Preprocessor
        preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
            transformers=[
                     ('categorical', categorical_transformer, categorical_features)
            ])
        
    
    
    pipeline = make_pipeline(preprocessor,
                         model)
    
    return pipeline

Modelling¶

In the project we are using one benchmark multiple regression model and three state of the art machine learning algorithms:

  1. Regression
  2. Random Forest
  3. xgboost
  4. CNN

First, the evaluation of those models needs to be set-up.
We are using Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) as the leading evaluation metric. Nevertheless, we are also considering further metrics to evaluate the models.

Nevertheless, we will not evalutate the model with $R^{2}$ because the implementation of sklearn can lead to negative values due to its definition.The expected boundry of 0 to 1 only holds true if a linear regression model is fit, and it is evaluated on the same data it is fitted on. Else, the definition of $R^{2}$ can lead to negative values. Since that makes $R^{2}$ based on sklearn a not ideal choice for evaluation. Further Reading

All advanced models are being run as base model, afterwards being tuned by random search and followed up by grid search or directly with grid search.

Setup Model Evaluation¶

In [182]:
evaluate = pd.DataFrame(columns=['model_name',
                                 'MAE', 
                                 'MSE',
                                 'RMSE',
                                 'MAPE',
#                                  'R2',
                                ])

def model_eval(model_name, y_pred, evaluate):
    evaluate = evaluate.append({'model_name':model_name,
                               'MAE':mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred),
                               'MSE':mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred),
                                'RMSE': np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)),
                               'MAPE':mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_test,y_pred)
#                                'R2':r2_score(y_test,y_pred)},ignore_index=True
                               }, ignore_index = True)
    return evaluate

def viz_eval(y_pred, label):
    x_ax = range(len(y_pred))
    plt.scatter(x_ax, y_test, s=5, color="blue", label="Original")
    plt.plot(x_ax, y_pred, lw=0.8, color="red", label=label)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Random Forest¶

Random Forest belongs to the ensemble learning models where multiple models are used to solve the same problem.

Therefore, it is a meta estimator that fits a number of decision tree classifiers on various random sub-samples of the dataset and uses averaging to improve the predictive accuracy and control over-fitting. 1

First, a base model is set up, then cross-validation and grid-search is used to tune the model. Since Random Forest does not require numerical standardization therefore it will not be done here.

Grid Search¶

The best parameters on the train data was achieved with 'randomforestregressor__n_estimators': 280, 'randomforestregressor__min_samples_split': 89, 'randomforestregressor__min_samples_leaf': 1, 'randomforestregressor__max_samples': 0.8, 'randomforestregressor__max_leaf_nodes': 45, 'randomforestregressor__max_features': 'auto', 'randomforestregressor__max_depth': 50, 'randomforestregressor__bootstrap': True

The tuned version of the model seems to have performed worse than the first base model. It seems the base model could have been a lucky overfitted result. We should assume that the tuned model is less overfitted and generalizes better. The tuned model slightly outperforms the Simple Regression model.

xgboost¶

XGBoost is an optimized distributed gradient boosting library designed to be highly efficient, flexible and portable. It implements machine learning algorithms under the Gradient Boosting framework. XGBoost provides a parallel tree boosting (also known as GBDT, GBM) that solve many data science problems in a fast and accurate way. As stated in the documentation it does not care much about the scale of the input features and therfore we will not standardize the numerical features [1].

[1] https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/

Deep Learning¶

As the last state-of-the-art approach we are using a Multi Layer Perception (MLP). MLP utilizes a supervised learning technique called backpropagation for training. Its multiple layers and non-linear activation distinguish MLP from a linear perceptron. It can distinguish data that is not linearly separable.MLP utilizes a supervised learning technique called backpropagation for training. Its multiple layers and non-linear activation distinguish MLP from a linear perceptron. It can distinguish data that is not linearly separable (‘Multilayer Perceptron’ 2023).

‘Multilayer Perceptron’. In Wikipedia, 6 February 2023. https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Multilayer_perceptron&oldid=1137841114 Page Version ID: 1137841114.

In [169]:
# Keras setup
# !pip install -U tensorflow==2.11.0
# !pip install tensorflow-cpu
# !pip install scikeras
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dropout
from scikeras.wrappers import KerasRegressor
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.constraints import MaxNorm
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

For setting up a neural network the question of how many hidden layers and how many neurons should be used. Literature suggests mostly an arbitrary choice but some rule of thumbs exist.

Based on Heaton (2017) these rule of thumbs exist:

Number of Hidden Layers:

Based on this we decide to use 3 hidden layers.

Number of Neurons:

  • The number of hidden neurons should be between the size of the input layer and the size of the output layer.
    From this rule of thumb we can derive a space of hidden neurons between 1-32.
  • The number of hidden neurons should be 2/3 the size of the input layer, plus the size of the output layer.
    From this rule of thumb we can derive a space of hidden neurons between 1-21.
  • The number of hidden neurons should be less than twice the size of the input layer.
    From this rule of thumb we can derive a space of hidden neurons between 1-16.

Based on that we will experiment with different configuration within the range of 1-32.

Generally, a large enough single layer network can approximate any other neural network, at least in theory.Generally, a large enough single layer network can approximate any other neural network, at least in theory.

This is way we have choosen a 24-12-8 layout of the hidden layers.

A common optimization algorithm is Adam. It is described as "computationally efficient, has little memory requirement, invariant to diagonal rescaling of gradients, and is well suited for problems that are large in terms of data/parameters"(Kingma et al., 2014). Therefore, we chose it for our model.

For the model tuning we use dropout to limit overfitting and to improve the model’s ability to generalize. For the best results, dropout is best combined with a weight constraint such as the max norm constraint.

Data scaling is a recommended pre-processing step when working with deep learning neural networks (Brownlee 2019). Therfore, we will use the StandardScalar in the Pipeline.

Source:
Heaton, Jeff. ‘The Number of Hidden Layers’. Heaton Research, 1 June 2017. https://www.heatonresearch.com/2017/06/01/hidden-layers.html.

Kingma, Diederik P., and Jimmy Ba. ‘Adam: A Method for Stochastic Optimization’. arXiv, 29 January 2017. https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1412.6980 arXiv:1412.6980 [cs].

Brownlee, Jason. 2019. ‘How to Use Data Scaling Improve Deep Learning Model Stability and Performance’. MachineLearningMastery.Com (blog). 3 February 2019. https://machinelearningmastery.com/how-to-improve-neural-network-stability-and-modeling-performance-with-data-scaling/.

%%time
# Build simple model
def create_model():
    model = Sequential()
    # Input layer and first hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(24, input_dim=32,activation='relu')) 
    # second hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(12, activation='relu')) 
    # third hidden layer
    model.add(Dense(8,activation='relu')) 
    # output layer
    model.add(Dense(1,activation='linear'))
    # compile model
    model.compile(loss="mean_squared_error", optimizer="adam")   
    return model

# fix random seed for reproducibility
seed = 42
tf.random.set_seed(seed)

# set up model
mlp_estimator = KerasRegressor(model=create_model, epochs=100, batch_size=10, verbose=0,random_state = 42)
mlp_pipeline = model_pipeline(mlp_estimator)
param_grid = {}
mlp_base = GridSearchCV(estimator=mlp_pipeline, param_grid=param_grid, scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', n_jobs=-1, cv=3)

# fit model
mlp_model_base = mlp_base.fit(X_train, y_train)

# define neural network
def create_model(optimizer='adam', activation='relu', init_mode='uniform'):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(24, input_dim=32, activation=activation, kernel_initializer=init_mode))
    model.add(Dense(12, activation=activation, kernel_initializer=init_mode))
    model.add(Dense(8, activation=activation, kernel_initializer=init_mode))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))
    model.compile(loss="mean_squared_error", optimizer=optimizer)
    return model

Summary¶

As we can see from the table below state-of-the-art models do not always deliver better results than well established simple methods.

We can see, that Random Forest performed best for our use case and MLP worst. Considering runtime, MLP is the most runtime consuming method whereas Simple Regression is the least.

We also saw that it is important to avoid data leakage and take appropriate measures to prevent it. Also we saw that Random Forest's base model delivered a better result on the testing set but those result did not seem stable and reproducable in hyperparameter tuning where avoiding overfitting was very important.

In gerneral, we can reasonably good predict the quality of coffee by only knowing its specifics available when purchasing.
